There are currently no further flights planned, but we will keep this under review. If you’re a British national and you require consular assistance, you should contact us on the details provided under Travel advice help and support
Sign up for email alerts and follow the British High Commission on Twitter and Facebook.
Help with booking
Do not contact the High Commission directly regarding flights. Our travel provider, CTM is organising the booking process on our behalf.
For further assistance send an SMS text message containing ONLY your full name to +44 7537 416 124 and someone from the CTM booking team will get in touch to assist you.
If you cannot pay the cost of the ticket, send an SMS text message containing ONLY your full name to +44 7537 416 124 and someone from the CTM team will get in touch to assist. If you have exhausted all other options available to you for getting funds, you may be eligible to apply for an emergency loan to cover the cost of the ticket. This is a last resort option and you would need to repay the loan when you are back in the UK. CTM are a commercial partner of the FCO and are authorised to administer such loans on behalf of the FCO.
If you are vulnerable and have registered your details with the High Commission you may receive a call about these flights. To protect you from scams, callers will identify themselves to you using personal information you have already submitted to the High Commission.
You may find it helpful to read our guide to eligibility and the booking process for special charter flights.
Medical clearance
The state Government of Kerala has advised any foreign nationals who have been in quarantine or self-isolation must have a medical clearance certificate before they can board outbound international flights. You must contact your local COVID 19 District Cell to begin the medical clearance process.
Travel to the airport
Do not travel to the airport without a confirmed ticket, as tickets will not be on sale at the airport.
Once you have a ticket, you will receive guidance on how to travel to the airport.
The British High Commission will provide transport to the airport for passengers where possible and submit the necessary permissions to the Indian government. The address that you provide will be where you are picked up from (unless you are asked to meet at a muster point), so you must provide accurate information.
You should not make your own way to the airport due to ongoing restrictions in India, unless in exceptional circumstances we are not able to arrange transport for you.
It may not be possible to buy food or water on the way to the airport, so get these before you travel.
You should allow plenty of time to get to the airport or your muster point as travelling may be more difficult than normal. You should make sure you are able to show authorities:
proof of a booked flight (a boarding pass if possible)
your passport
At the airport
You will not be able to travel if you are currently showing coronavirus symptoms (you will need to self-isolate and travel later). There will be mandatory healthcare screening at the airport. You should comply with any additional screening measures put in place by the authorities prior to your departure. If you travel to the airport when you have symptoms, you may be moved to a mandatory quarantine facility for further testing.
Arrival in the UK
When you arrive back in the UK, follow the guidance for when you return to the UK on steps you should take to protect yourself and others.
Future options
The British High Commission is in contact with airlines, the Indian authorities and other governments to make sure commercial options for returning to the UK are available as soon as possible.
Booking portals for UK special flights have now closed. If you require urgent consular assistance, please contact us as set out in the Travel advice help and support section.
If you cannot leave India at this time, you should:
follow the advice of local authorities, including local measures to help minimise your risk of exposure to coronavirus - comply with local isolation, testing or quarantine requirements, and to rely on the local health system
find accommodation that’s suitable for your needs. Unless you have an urgent reason to travel within India, you may need to stay where you are whilst the flight ban and lockdowns remain in place
check the validity of your Indian visa. If it has or is due to expire you will need to apply online for an extension at E-FRRO
be aware that many additional restrictions are being introduced at state level. Some states are not allowing foreign nationals to either enter or exit. No flights, trains or any form of public transport are operational. Hotels in some states have been instructed to refuse entry to foreign nationals. British Nationals opting for repatriation through special flights are being allowed to travel with special permission obtained by the British High Commission from the Indian Ministry of External Affairs.
keep in regular contact with family and friends at home, so they know you are safe and well
The situation remains fluid. You should continue to monitor the local advice on any state level restrictions and follow the instructions of the local authorities.
See more information and advice about staying where you are if you cannot return to the UK.
Staying in where you are
Accommodation
If your hotel asks you to leave, ask them to provide alternative accommodation, or talk to the police who can assist. If you have nowhere to go and you need urgent help, contact the nearest British consulate:
New Delhi: +91 (11) 2419 2100
Chennai: + 91 (44) 42192151
Mumbai/Goa: +91 (22) 6650 2222
Food and medicine
The Government of India has ordered that food, medicines and other supplies remain available, but we are aware that supplies are running low, and some shops are closed.
If you need medicine, use Google to find nearby pharmacies and ask if they will deliver. If not, you should walk (not drive) to the nearest pharmacy or ask your accommodation provider to help. Carry any medical papers or prescriptions and be prepared to answer questions if stopped by the police. If your usual medication is not available, consult a local doctor for an Indian alternative or go to the nearest hospital. In a genuine medical emergency, call an ambulance.
Goa
In Goa there is a lockdown and curfew, meaning if you are outdoors you may be stopped and detained by authorities. You should stay indoors as far as possible. If you need to go out, be prepared to explain why if you are stopped.
The Goa State Government has set up the following helplines:
food requests +91 9423890066
medicine requests +91 7823026971
food deliveries in North Goa +91 94238 90077 (WhatsApp and Telegram only)
The authorities have also confirmed that small shops will be open throughout Goa and people are allowed to walk to these to buy essentials. If you require urgent consular assistance in Goa, call our consular helpline on +91 (22) 6650 2222.
Punjab
The Punjab government has asked foreign travellers who have arrived in Punjab after 30 January 2020 to provide the following details. This is essential for those who have not been contacted by civil administration, health and police department so far. Details can be submitted on dial-112@punjabpolice.gov.in or on WhatsApp number +91 9779920404.
